            deepDive: "MK-677 (Ibutamoren) is a non-peptide spiropiperidine that acts as a potent, long-acting, orally active, and selective agonist of the ghrelin/growth hormone secretagogue receptor (GHS-R1a).\n\nReceptor Binding: It binds specifically to the GHS-R1a receptor in the pituitary and hypothalamus, mimicking the action of endogenous ghrelin.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has an exceptionally long half-life of approximately 24 hours. A single oral dose maintains elevated IGF-1 levels for a full 24-hour period.\n\nSelectivity: It stimulates GH release with minimal effect on cortisol or prolactin levels (though slight elevations in prolactin are occasionally observed in clinical practice).\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nUnlike injectable GHRPs which cause a sharp, short-lived 'pulse' of GH, MK-677 amplifies the basal pulsatile release of GH over a 24-hour period. It increases the amplitude of the natural GH pulses without altering the pulse frequency. This sustained elevation of GH leads to a steady, continuous rise in systemic IGF-1 levels produced by the liver.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nA landmark 2-year, double-blind, placebo-controlled study in healthy older adults showed that 25mg daily significantly increased GH and IGF-1 levels to those of young adults without serious adverse effects. Trials have shown it increases bone turnover and eventually bone mineral density. It was studied for Alzheimer's disease (due to IGF-1's neuroprotective effects) but failed to show clinical improvement in disease progression.\n\nThe Insulin Resistance Problem:\nThe primary drawback of MK-677 is its effect on glucose metabolism. Continuous elevation of GH antagonizes insulin action in skeletal muscle and the liver. In clinical trials, fasting blood glucose and HbA1c levels consistently rose in subjects taking MK-677. This is why concurrent use of insulin-sensitizing agents (like Berberine or Metformin) is highly recommended.",
