            deepDive: "Hexarelin (Examorelin) is a synthetic hexapeptide (His-D-2-methyl-Trp-Ala-Trp-D-Phe-Lys-NH2). It is a highly potent agonist of the ghrelin/growth hormone secretagogue receptor (GHS-R1a) and the CD36 receptor.\n\nReceptor Binding: It binds to the GHS-R1a receptor in the pituitary to stimulate GH release. Crucially, it also binds with high affinity to the CD36 receptor, a scavenger receptor heavily expressed in cardiac tissue.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has an elimination half-life of approximately 55 to 75 minutes following subcutaneous administration.\n\nSelectivity: Hexarelin is not selective. It causes a massive, dose-dependent increase in GH, but also significantly elevates ACTH (leading to cortisol release) and prolactin.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\n\nGH Release: Binding to the GHS-R1a receptor activates the PLC/PKC pathway, leading to calcium influx and immediate GH vesicle release. It is the most potent GHRP in terms of peak GH amplitude.\n\nCardiovascular Protection: Hexarelin's binding to the CD36 receptor in the heart provides direct cardioprotective effects. In animal models, it has been shown to protect against ischemic injury, reduce myocardial infarct size, prevent cardiac fibrosis, and improve left ventricular ejection fraction. These effects occur independently of GH release (they occur even in GH-deficient animals).\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nIn human trials, Hexarelin demonstrated the highest peak GH release of any GHRP. However, trials also confirmed rapid receptor desensitization; the GH response blunts significantly after 4-14 days of continuous use, requiring a washout period to restore sensitivity.\n\nSynergy with GHRH: Hexarelin and CJC-1295 trigger GH release through completely different intracellular pathways. When used together, they produce a massive, synergistic GH pulse.\n\nLong-Term Use Data:\nLong-term use is impossible due to rapid receptor downregulation. It must be cycled strictly (e.g., 4 weeks on, 4 weeks off).",
