            deepDive: "TB-500 is a synthetic fraction of the naturally occurring protein Thymosin Beta-4 (Tβ4). Tβ4 is a 43-amino acid protein encoded by the TMSB4X gene.\n\nThe Fragment Debate: True Tβ4 is 43 amino acids long. 'TB-500' originally referred to a specific 7-amino acid active fragment (LKKTETQ) of Tβ4. However, in the modern research chemical market, vendors often sell the full 43-amino acid Tβ4 sequence under the name 'TB-500.' Both are effective, but the full sequence is generally preferred for comprehensive healing.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has a relatively long half-life and exerts prolonged biological effects, which is why it only needs to be dosed twice a week.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nTB-500's primary mechanism of action is actin regulation.\n\n1. Actin Sequestration: Actin is a protein that forms the structural scaffolding of cells. TB-500 binds to G-actin, preventing it from polymerizing into F-actin. This keeps the cellular scaffolding fluid, allowing cells (like fibroblasts and myoblasts) to migrate rapidly to the site of an injury.\n\n2. Angiogenesis: Like BPC-157, it promotes the formation of new blood vessels, but via different pathways.\n\n3. Anti-Inflammatory: It significantly downregulates inflammatory cytokines and chemokines, providing massive systemic relief from inflammation.\n\n4. Stem Cell Differentiation: It has been shown to promote the differentiation of stem cells in hair follicles and cardiac tissue.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nTβ4 has undergone Phase II clinical trials for the treatment of pressure ulcers, stasis ulcers, and epidermolysis bullosa (a severe skin blistering disease). It showed significant acceleration in wound healing. It has also been studied as an eye drop for dry eye syndrome and neurotrophic keratitis.\n\nCardiac Repair: Preclinical models show Tβ4 can promote the survival of cardiomyocytes after a myocardial infarction (heart attack) by activating epicardial progenitor cells.\n\nSynergy with BPC-157: The combination is legendary because they attack healing from two different angles. BPC-157 upregulates growth factor receptors and promotes angiogenesis, while TB-500 provides the cellular mobility (via actin) for the repair cells to actually reach the injury site and do the work.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: There is no long-term safety data in humans for systemic injection. Due to the theoretical risk of unchecked angiogenesis (tumor promotion), continuous, year-round use is strongly discouraged.",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Is TB-500 the same thing as Thymosin Beta-4?", answer: "Technically, no. TB-500 is a specific fragment of the larger Thymosin Beta-4 protein. However, in the peptide market today, the names are used interchangeably, and most vials labeled 'TB-500' actually contain the full Thymosin Beta-4 sequence."),
                FAQItem(question: "Do I have to inject it right into the muscle tear?", answer: "Absolutely not. TB-500 is highly systemic. It has a low molecular weight and travels easily through the bloodstream to find areas of inflammation and injury. Injecting it into your belly fat will heal a torn hamstring perfectly well."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do I only inject it twice a week instead of every day like BPC-157?", answer: "TB-500 has a much longer half-life and its effects on actin regulation persist for days. Daily injection is unnecessary and wastes expensive peptide."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I mix BPC-157 and TB-500 in the same syringe?", answer: "Yes. Many users draw both peptides into the same insulin syringe to reduce the number of injections. They do not degrade each other in the syringe."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will it cure my arthritis?", answer: "TB-500 is excellent for reducing the systemic inflammation associated with arthritis, which can provide massive pain relief. However, it cannot regrow lost cartilage (bone-on-bone arthritis)."),
