                FAQItem(question: "Why does the injection hurt so much?", answer: "Copper is a heavy metal and is highly irritating to subcutaneous tissue. The body reacts to the sudden localized concentration of copper with an immediate inflammatory pain response. Diluting the injection with extra water or BPC-157 spreads the copper out, reducing the irritation."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I just take a copper supplement pill instead?", answer: "No. Taking oral copper supplements will increase your systemic copper levels, but it will not provide the specific gene-modulating effects of the GHK tripeptide. The magic is in the combination of the GHK peptide delivering the copper directly into the cells."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will it fix my baldness?", answer: "If your hair follicles are completely dead and scarred over, no. If your hair is thinning (miniaturization of the follicles), topical GHK-Cu (especially combined with microneedling) has been clinically proven to enlarge the follicles and stimulate new growth."),
                FAQItem(question: "My GHK-Cu powder is white, not blue. Is it fake?", answer: "Yes. GHK without the copper attached is white. But GHK-Cu (with the copper bound to it) is always a distinct, vibrant blue. If it is white, you were sold plain GHK or a completely different powder."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I use it while taking GLP-1s like Semaglutide?", answer: "Yes, this is highly recommended. GLP-1s cause rapid weight loss, which often leads to loose, sagging skin. GHK-Cu upregulates collagen and elastin production, helping the skin tighten as you lose the fat."),
