            deepDive: "Retatrutide (LY3437943) is a 39-amino acid synthetic peptide with a C20 fatty diacid moiety attached, similar to Tirzepatide, which extends its half-life to approximately 6 days.\n\nReceptor Affinity: It is a single molecule engineered to bind to three distinct receptors. It is highly potent at the GIP receptor (EC50: 0.0643 nM), moderately potent at the GLP-1 receptor (EC50: 0.775 nM), and has a lower, but clinically significant, potency at the Glucagon receptor (EC50: 5.79 nM).\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nThe addition of the Glucagon receptor agonism is what separates Retatrutide from its predecessors.\n\n1. GLP-1 & GIP: As with Tirzepatide, these receptors handle appetite suppression, delayed gastric emptying, and glucose-dependent insulin secretion.\n\n2. Glucagon Receptor (GCGR): Historically, Glucagon was thought to be bad for diabetics because it raises blood sugar. However, when combined with GLP-1 and GIP (which lower blood sugar), the glycemic effect is neutralized. What remains are the other effects of Glucagon:\n\n- Increased Energy Expenditure: GCGR activation increases the basal metabolic rate by stimulating brown adipose tissue (BAT) thermogenesis.\n- Hepatic Lipid Clearance: GCGR activation in the liver profoundly stimulates beta-oxidation (fat burning) and inhibits lipogenesis. This leads to a rapid and massive reduction in liver fat (steatosis).\n\nThe \"Triple\" Balance: The genius of Retatrutide is the precise balancing of the three receptor affinities. Too much Glucagon agonism would cause hyperglycemia; too little would fail to increase energy expenditure. The current ratio provides massive fat loss while maintaining excellent glycemic control.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: Because it is still in Phase 3 trials, long-term (multi-year) safety data is not yet available. The primary long-term monitoring focus will be on cardiovascular outcomes due to the sustained increase in resting heart rate.",
